systemctl, and reading status.

systemctl is the one command you'll use for almost every interaction with systemd. Its shape is just: systemctl, a verb, and usually a unit name.

Let's run through the verbs you'll use daily. status shows a unit's current state plus its most recent log lines. start, stop, and restart do exactly what they say, right now, though temporarily. reload tells a service to re-read its config without actually restarting, if the service supports that. enable and disable control whether a unit starts at boot. And a lovely shortcut, enable dash-dash-now, both enables the unit for boot and starts it immediately, in one command. There are also scriptable checks like is-active and is-enabled. cat shows you a unit file, and edit opens a drop-in override. And daemon-reload re-reads all the unit files from disk.

Which brings us to the single most important rule in this whole module. After you create or edit a unit file, you must run systemctl daemon-reload before you try to start or restart the service. Why? Because systemd caches unit definitions in memory. Without a daemon-reload, it simply won't see your change on disk. So whenever you edit something and the service stubbornly doesn't pick it up, your first two checks are always: did I run daemon-reload? And did I run restart, rather than just reload?

Now, reading systemctl status, because it's your first move when investigating any service. At the top there's a coloured dot: green means active, red means failed, white means inactive. The Loaded line tells you where the unit file is and whether it's enabled, meaning it starts at boot, or disabled. The Active line is the runtime state, and there are a few you'll see: active-running is the healthy one; active-exited means a one-shot unit finished successfully; inactive-dead means it's just not running; and failed means it crashed or exited with an error. And here's the genuinely useful part: status prints the service's last several log lines right there at the bottom. So when a service has failed, you look right there first, and then run journalctl dash-u, the unit name, to see more.
